<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0" bgcolor=""  width="95%" align="center"><tr><td>
<table cellpadding="4" cellspacing="1" border="0"  width="100%">
<tr>
	<td bgcolor="#DEDFDF" width="175" valign="top" nowrap>
	<a name="post202084"></a>
	
	<font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial"><b>Caelia</b></font><br>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Diplomat</font><br>
	<p>
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial">Registered: Sep 2002<br>
	Location: Linköping, Sweden<br>
	Posts: 662</font></td>
	
	<td bgcolor="#DEDFDF" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font size="1" face="Verdana, Arial"> <b></b></font>
	<p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">I've toyed with the idea of testing aggro on heals as well, but I haven't been able to find a reliable way to check it. My basic idea, however was to have one person draw aggro with a spell, and then see what it takes to "overcome" that aggro. The problem with this is that we do not know the amount of aggro generated by a specific spell, and so the best we could do would be to be able to say "Supernal Remedy is equivalent aggro to 2 Fears" or "A 5k complete heal equals 3 snares".<br />
<br />
But with some decently set-up test scenarios, the question of "does amount of HP healed matter for aggro" should be able to be answered.<br />
<br />
Here's something else that I've wondered at times: Is aggro generated by a heal a function of the aggro currently held by the person healed? I.e. does healing a druid that only has proximity aggro give as much aggro as a warrior who have been using a Blade of War on a mob for 30 minutes?</font></p>
	
	<p><p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial">__________________<br>
